News Editor

Some of the vendors with whom

Pitt ended contracts on Nov. 1 might

return to campus as early as
Thanksgiving, operating under . new
guidelines put forth by a committee
forming to study and make decisions
about vending here.

Others won’t be allowed to come
back at all.

"Pitt held a press conference Friday
to explain its decision to eliminate —

‘perhaps temporarily + the vendors who

operate in front of the William Pitt
Union.

The press conference outlined some
of the reasons for the decision, and for
the first time since vendors were
informed of that decision, suggested
that some might be allowed to return.

ii But that return will be accompanied
by more rigid guidelines than have gov-
erned vending for most of the last two
decades. Those guidelines, which
University spokesman Robert Hill said
Pitt hopes to institute by Thanksgiving,
will be determined by a committee

made up of University administrators.

and .at least one student: Student
Government Board President Jeff Alex.

Alex declined to comment, pending

a meeting with Associate Vice

Chancellor for Business Eli Shorak,
who will head the committee. '

\ And though that committee has yet

to convene, the University outlined

some of those policies in a press confer-

ence.

Returning vendors will be required
to obtain insurance coverage and the
appropriate vending licenses. They will
not be able to vend goods or services in
a way that conﬂicts with Pitt’s contracts
with large companies, such as PepsiCo
Inc. The University has a standing con-
tract with the beverage provider that

prohibits the sale or dispensation of cer- .

tain competitors’ beverage products.

Merchants will also be required to
sell goods that meet “minimum stan-
dards of quality,” and offer products or
services “that are of express interest to
students,” and that maximize the benefit
to the entire“ University community,
according to a University press release.

Hill also said there will be a limit on
the total number of vendors allowed to
participate in the program.

