University vending options

Vendors, page 1

came about because a number of fac-
tors.
Hill mentioned a change in leader-

~ ship within the Office of Student

Activities as one push for a re—evalua-
tion of vending at Pitt. Jack Daniel, now
the interim dean of students — a posi-
tion that oversees the Ofﬁce of Student
Activities —— began working as dean of
students in early September.

Hill also focused on a disorganized
application process and issues of
University liability as forces driving the
change.

“Right now, the process is not
orderly,” Hill said, adding that there is

“no standard for [determining] who may
vend.” '

According to Hill, an unspeciﬁed
number of students have also lodged
complaints about the merchandise some
vendors offer for sale. In response to
those complaints, Hill said, “the new
leadership in student affairs decided to
do something about it.”

The attractiveness of the physical

' environment created by vendors is also

an issue, Hill said.

“Physical facilities and attractive-
ness areissues. We are competing with
major Universities across the country,”
Hill said. “We want attractive infrastruc-
tures, not rickety folding tables.”

_Asked specifically whether some
Pitt administrators prompted the change
because of concern that the vendors
look tacky, Hill said that appearance
was a consideration.

“Nobody in the administration likes

‘g rickety tables,” he said.

Responding to concerns that Pitt
failed to inform vendors of the reason
for their "dismissal from campus, Hill
said the terrorist attacks of Sept. 11 hin-
dered a coordinated line of communica-
tion between the school and the ven-
dors.

Hill said that if the Sept. 11 attacks
had never happened, the University’s

' original plan to carry out a more com-

prehensive review of the vendors would
have been put into place, but that con-
cerns for students’ safety and security
after the attacks consumed the time and
resources of the administrative commu-
nity.

Hill stressed that while many vend-
ing guidelines will change, the money
generated by leasing vending spaces
will still go to student programs and
activities, but won’t necessarily contin-
ue to be directed to the Student
Organization Resource Center. A ,

Before vendors were removed from
campus Nov. 1, Pitt proﬁted between
$50 and $100 per vendor per day. That
money funded SORC, which certiﬁes
and assists student organizations at Pitt.

The amount charged to vendors
may also change, Hill said.

Dolly Franzos, who until Thursday
sold jewelry in front of the Union, said
she remains hopeful that Pitt will work
the situation out in the best interests of
everyone involved. Franzos said that
provided the new regulations aren’t
overburdening, she would love to return
to campus. A

But because she barely broke even
on slower sales days, Franzos said she
won’t be able to return if insurance pre-
miums and new University fees are too
high. .

Franzos said that she never imag-
ined the outpouring of student support
that followed the University’s decision

to oust Union vendors. She received
‘ﬂowers, gifts and cards in the mail.

Hill couldn’t specify how the 7

changes will affectspeciﬁc vendors, but
that Pitt’s hope is that vendors “that stu-
dents have come to love over the years”
will return to campus.

— Staﬁ‘ writer Kate Giammarise con-
tributed to this report.

